## PART 4 — Which TensorBoard graphs to watch (and how to read them)

| Graph | GOING WELL | EXPLOSION (this issue) | VANISHING (the tanh failure) |
|---|---|---|---|
| **`Grad/total_norm`** | steady, bounded (e.g. < a few) | spikes upward, then loss → NaN | collapses toward 0 and stays there |
| **`Args/std_i`** (per head) | small but **non-zero**, stable | the bad head's mean drifts toward ±1 | std → 0 (head is **dead/frozen**) |
| **`Args/mean_i`** (per head) | settles near data-realistic values | marches to ±1 (toward the singularity) | flat / stuck at init |
| **`Loss/train_*`** | decreasing then plateau | fine, then **sudden jump to NaN** | **rising** or stuck (the tanh symptom) |
| **`Loss/val`** | decreasing, tracks train | NaN once weights poison | rising / flat |
| **`Loss/raw_filter_i`** | each filter's loss active | the unstable filter's loss erratic before NaN | early filters **inert/flat** (chained-clamp starvation) |
| **`Metrics/PSNR`, `SSIM`, `MSE`, `fMSE`** | PSNR/SSIM up, MSE/fMSE down toward paper | collapse to NaN | stall / worsen |

**How to confirm the diagnosis from the graphs:**
- **It's the explosion (this NaN):** `Grad/total_norm` trends up over epochs and one `Args/mean_i`
  walks toward ±1, *then* `Loss/train` jumps to NaN. The head whose `Args/mean_i` hit ±1 is the
  culprit filter — confirm it's Tint/Brightness/curve/hue.
- **It's vanishing (the tanh fix backfiring):** `Grad/total_norm` → 0, one or more `Args/std_i` → 0,
  and `Loss/train` flat or **rising**. That means a head is frozen — loosen the bound / drop tanh.
- **It's actually going well:** `Grad/total_norm` bounded and stable, every `Args/std_i` non-zero,
  `Loss/val` decreasing, `Metrics/PSNR` & `SSIM` rising toward paper level with no NaN.

**One-liner:** watch `Grad/total_norm` + each head's `Args/mean`/`Args/std` — rising norm with an
arg-mean drifting to ±1 = the explosion you're chasing; norm → 0 with arg-std → 0 = the tanh-style
vanishing; bounded norm with non-zero arg-std and falling `Loss/val` = healthy.
